Seismic Behavior of Buildings Located on Slopes - An Analytical Study and Some Observations From Sikkim Earthquake of September 18, 2011

The focus of the analytical study on the seismic behavior of buildings located on slopes and the observations from the Sikkim Earthquake of September 18, 2011, was to examine the dynamic characteristics and seismic behavior of hill buildings using modal, linear, and nonlinear time history analyses. The study aimed to understand the peculiar seismic behavior of hill buildings due to their irregular and unsymmetrical structural configurations on hill slopes. The findings of the analytical study were corroborated by observations during damage surveys after the Sikkim earthquake.

explain Active vibration control of a smart structure

Active vibration control of a smart structure involves using sensors and actuators within the structure to actively manage and reduce vibrations. In the context of smart truss structures, such as those with piezoelectric (PZT) active bars, the active bar can act as both an actuator for vibration excitation and a sensor for vibration measurement. The optimal placement of these active bars is crucial for the structural design phase, shape, and vibration control. By strategically placing these active bars and using feedback control systems, the structure can actively counteract vibrations, leading to improved performance and safety.

Who is SC MOHAN

S.C. Mohan is an Assistant Professor in the Department of Civil Engineering at BITS-Pilani, Hyderabad. He received his PhD degree from IIT Kharagpur, India. His research interests include structural dynamics, earthquake and vibration control, structural health monitoring, computational cost reduction, and the development of low-cost base-isolation systems for low-rise RC and masonry buildings.
